e questioned about their competence in both their public and private lives. If they don’t, they face criticism for not understanding or relating to key policy domains. This “damned if you do, damned if you don’t” conundrum raises difficult questions about the intersection of gender, parental status, and politics. Mothers and Others examines key areas of citizen engagement with the political system – political careers, the media, and political behaviour – to argue that being a parent is a gendered political identity that influences how, why, and to what extent women (and men) engage with politics. The first major comparative analysis of the role of parenthood in politics, Mothers and Others makes important observations about what we know and what we still need to find out.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFatherhoodxPolitical aspects. 0aFathersxPolitical activity. 0aMotherhoodxPolitical aspects. 0aMothersxPolitical activity. 0aParenthoodxPolitical aspects. 0aParentsxPolitical activity. 0aPolitical culture. 0aPolitical sociology. 0aPress and politics. 0aWomenxPolitical activity. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aArneil, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBittner, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBittner, Amanda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Rosie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilds, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeason, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranceschet, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGidengil, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aG